$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
        Substitution
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

$(
   Now we come to the concept of proper substitution.

   For our notation, we use ` ( ph x | y ) ` to mean "the wff that results
   when ` y ` is properly substituted for ` x ` in the wff ` ph `."  The
   placement of parentheses is slightly different than in the notation
   ` ph ( x | y ) ` that is sometimes used, because the latter notation is
   ambiguous for us:  for example, we don't know whether ` -. ph ( x | y ) ` is
   to be interpreted as ` -. ( ph x | y ) ` or ` ( -. ph x | y ) `.  (Because
   of the way we have defined ` wff `, this is the case with all "postfix"
   wff operators.)
$)

  $( Declare a new symbol first used by the substitution notation. $)
  $c | $.  $( Vertical bar $)

  $( Extend wff definition to include proper substitution (read "the wff that
     results when ` y ` is properly substituted for ` x ` in wff ` ph `"). $)
  wsb $a wff ( ph x | y ) $.

  $( Define proper substitution.    Remark 9.1 in Megill,
   p. 447.  For our notation, we use ` ( ph x | y ) ` to
   mean "the wff that results when ` y ` is properly substituted for ` x ` in
   the wff ` ph `."  Some authors use the notation ` [ y / x ] ph `, which
   would also work for us without ambiguity (and is used in the Metamath
   Solitaire applet).  Logic texts usually introduce substitution as a new
   primitive notion described informally, such as "replace all free
   occurrences of variable ` x ` with variable ` y `, renaming bound variables
   as needed."  The technical details of the standard definition are somewhat
   complex for what is supposed to be a primitive notion.  Rather than
   introduce a new primitive notion, we will define substitution using the
   existing language.  Then we will show that our definition has the
   properties we expect of substitution (see theorems ~sbid , ~sbequ , ~sbcocv
   and ~sbco0v ).  Note that our definition is valid even when ` x ` and ` y `
   are replaced with the same variable.  The first conjunct is a trick used to
   achieve this property, making the definition look somewhat odd at first. $)
  df-sb $a |- ( ( ph x | y ) <->
              ( ( x = y -> ph ) /\ E. x ( x = y /\ ph ) ) ) $.

