$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
                 The Axiom of Infinity
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

  $( sci.logic 10/30/96
>Does the statement
>  "There exists a non-empty set that is a subset of its union"
>imply the Axiom of Infinity under ZF-Inf (without using Choice)?

(Here is an accurate proof of this.  I broke it up into small lemmas to
make it easy to follow.  Thanks to Richard Heck for assistance and to
Ian Sutherland, who sent me a somewhat more sophisticated proof that I
took the key ideas from.)

Yes.  Let X be a nonempty set which is a subset of its union; the latter
property is equivalent to saying that for any y in X, there exists a z in X
such that y is in z.

Define by finite recursion a function F:omega-->(power X) such that
  F_0 = 0
  F_n+1 = {y<X | y^X subset F_n}    (^ means intersect, < is \in)
(Finite recursion as typically done requires the existence of omega;
to avoid this we can just use transfinite recursion restricted to omega.
F is a class-term that is not necessarily a set at this point.)

Lemma 1.  F_n subset F_n+1.
Proof:  By induction:  F_0 subset F_1.  If y < F_n+1, then y^X subset F_n,
so if F_n subset F_n+1, then y^X subset F_n+1, so y < F_n+2.

Lemma 2.  F_n =/= X.
Proof:  By induction:  F_0 =/= X because X is not empty.  Assume F_n =/= X.
Then there is a y in X that is not in F_n.  By definition of X, there is a
z in X that contains y.  Suppose F_n+1 = X.  Then z is in F_n+1, and z^X
contains y, so z^X is not a subset of F_n, contrary to the definition of
F_n+1.

Lemma 3.  F_n =/= F_n+1.
Proof:  Using the identity y^X subset F_n <-> y^(X-F_n) = 0, we have
F_n+1 = {y<X | y^(X-F_n) = 0}.  Let q = {y<X-F_n | y^(X-F_n) = 0}.  Then q
subset F_n+1.  Since X-F_n is not empty by Lemma 2 and q is the set of
\in-minimal elements of X-F_n, by Foundation q is not empty, so q and
therefore F_n+1 have an element not in F_n.

Lemma 4.  F_n proper_subset F_n+1.
Proof:  Lemmas 1 and 3.

Lemma 5.  F_m proper_subset F_n, m < n.
Proof:  Fix m and use induction on n > m.  Basis: F_m proper_subset F_m+1
by Lemma 4.  Induction:  Assume F_m proper_subset F_n.  Then since F_n
proper_subset F_n+1, F_m proper_subset F_n+1 by transitivity of proper
subset.

By Lemma 5, F_m =/= F_n for m =/= n, so F is 1-1.  Thus the inverse of F is
a function with range omega and domain a subset of power X, so omega exists
by Replacement.

Norm ndm@shore.net
  $)

